Vietnamese Coffee Premium Said to Drop 27% in Week on Supply

-- B y   I s i s   A l m e i d a
-- 
2011-07-08T17:08:36Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-08/vietnamese-coffee-premium-said-to-drop-27-in-week-on-supply.html
The premium buyers are prepared to
pay for robusta coffee from  Vietnam , the world’s biggest
producer, fell as much as 27 percent in the past week as sales
accelerated, according to three people involved in the trade.  Vietnamese beans are trading in Europe at $110 to $130 a
metric ton above the price on the NYSE Liffe exchange in  London ,
according to the people, who declined to be identified because
they aren’t authorized to speak to the media. The premium was
$150 a week ago, Volcafe, the coffee unit of commodities trader
ED&F Man Holdings Ltd., said July 1.  Robusta coffee for September delivery dropped $26, or 1.1
percent, to $2,437 a ton on NYSE Liffe in London. The price has
climbed 16 percent this year.  Vietnam’s robusta coffee production for the 2010-11 season
that started in October is estimated at 18.2 million bags by the
 U.S. Department of Agriculture .  To contact the reporter on this story:
Isis Almeida in London at 
 Ialmeida3@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
